    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-03-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-03-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="341"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d341">
                <head>341. Intelligence Information Cable<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d341fn1"
                        >Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Country File, United
                        Nations, Article 19, Vol. 2. Secret; No Foreign Dissem; Controlled Dissem;
                        No Dissem Abroad; Background Use Only. Prepared in the Central Intelligence
                        Agency.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">TDCS DB–315/00729–65</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-03-03">March 3, 1965</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>COUNTRY</head>
                    <item>United Nations</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>DATE OF INFO.</head>
                    <item>Late February 1965</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>1. Activities Affecting the United Nations</item>
                    <item>2. Views of the United Nations Secretary General and Assembly President on
                        Chances for a Successful Negotiation of <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                        Financial Problem</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>PLACE &amp; DATE ACQ.</head>
                    <item>1 March 1965</item>
                    <item> [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line of source text not declassified</hi>] </item>
                    <item> [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line of source text not declassified</hi>]
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SOURCE AND APPRAISAL</head>
                    <item> [<hi rend="italic">8 lines of source text not declassified</hi>] </item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>United Nations General Assembly President <persName corresp="#p_QSA1">Alex
                            Quaison-Sackey</persName> and Secretary General <persName
                            corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName> are currently wondering if the
                        newly-formed United Nations Committee on Peace-Keeping Operations (Committee
                        of 33) will be able to operate effectively in the atmosphere created by the
                        Vietnam crisis. United States military operations in Vietnam seem to be
                        bringing about a hardening of the Soviet attitude toward the United States.
                        The situation appears to be getting worse despite the fact that the United
                        States made a major concession to the Soviets by agreeing to exclude
                        Nationalist China from participation on the Committee.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_QSA1">Quaison-Sackey</persName> originally planned to
                        contact personally the French, Soviet, British and United States permanent
                        missions to the United Nations in order to lay a solid groundwork for the
                        Committee of 33 prior to the Committee’s meetings. However, <persName
                            corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_QSA1"
                            >Quaison-Sackey</persName> now feel that in view of the Vietnam crisis,
                        it is pointless to approach the Soviet Union because the Soviets will
                        probably not be very cooperative. Under these circumstances, <persName
                            corresp="#p_QSA1">Quaison-Sackey</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName> feel that the Committee of 33 will
                        not accomplish anything. ([<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line of source text
                            not declassified</hi>] Comment: <pb facs="0777" n="743" xml:id="pg_743"
                        /> According to the intermediate source, [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line
                            of source text not declassified</hi>] heard that an unknown country has
                        already advised <persName corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_QSA1">Quaison-Sackey</persName> that the Soviets will not be
                        receptive to any approaches on peace-keeping matters at this time.)</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Field Dissem: Sent <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
